oduce these excess fluctuations is instead a\npower law, the density contrast drho/rho implied by the excess fluctuations\nreveals that the Universe is smooth and linear on scales of tens of Mpc, while\nit can be highly non-linear on scales ~1 Mpc.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 29 Oct 1996 10:14:31 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 31 Oct 1996 09:34:31 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 11 Dec 1996 18:47:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-24"}
{"id":"cond-mat/9610198","submitter":"Markku I. Salkola","authors":"M.I. Salkola, A.V. Balatsky, and J.R. Schrieffer","title":"Spectral Properties of Quasiparticle Excitations Induced by Magnetic\n  Moments in Superconductors","comments":"to appear in Phys. Rev. B55, May 1st (1997)","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.55.12648","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.supr-con","license":null,"abstract":"  The consequences of localized, classical magnetic moments in superconductors\nare explored and their effect on the spectral properties of the intragap bound\nstates is studied. Above a critical moment, a localized quasiparticle\nexcitation in an s-wave superconductor is spontaneously created near a magnetic\nimpurity, inducing a zero-temperature quantum transition. In this transition,\nthe spin quantum number of the ground state changes from zero to 1/2, while the\ntotal charge remains the same. In contrast, the spin-unpolarized ground state\nof a d-wave superconductor is found to be stable for any value of the magnetic\nmoment when the normal-state energy spectrum possesses particle-hole symmetry.\nThe effect of impurity scattering on the quasiparticle states is interpreted in\nthe spirit of relevant symmetries of the clean superconductor. The results\nobtained by the non-self-consistent (T matrix) and the self-consistent\nmean-field approximations are compared and qualitative agreement between the\ntwo schemes is found in the regime where the coherence length is longer than\nthe Fermi length.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 29 Oct 1996 01:40:57 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 4 Feb 1997 04:50:54 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-08-31"}
